re. We define the cores to encompass molecular\ngas, which is additionally highly shielded. Most cores are in\ngravitational-kinetic equipartition and are already well described by the\ncommon virial parameter $\\alpha_\\mathrm{vir}$ (as can be seen from the Heyer\nrelation), while some undergo minor dispersion by kinetic surface effects.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 24 Aug 2022 18:00:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-26"}
{"id":"2208.11706","submitter":"Batoul Banihashemi","authors":"Batoul Banihashemi, Ted Jacobson, Andrew Svesko and Manus Visser","title":"The minus sign in the first law of de Sitter horizons","comments":"13 pages plus appendices, 5 figures; v2: multiple minor improvements\n  made, particularly in section 3.1; v3: published version. Discussion of\n  taking the zero boundary radius limit through a sequence of metastable\n  configurations added in Section 2 and Appendix C, and several minor\n  clarifications added","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/JHEP01(2023)054","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Due to a well-known, but curious, minus sign in the Gibbons-Hawking first law\nfor the static patch of de Sitter space, the entropy of the cosmological\nhorizon is reduced by the addition of Killing energy. This minus sign raises\nthe puzzling question how the thermodynamics of the static patch should be\nunderstood. We argue the confusion arises because of a mistaken interpretation\nof the matter Killing energy as the total internal energy, and resolve the\npuzzle by introducing a system boundary at which a proper thermodynamic\nensemble can be specified. When this boundary shrinks to zero size the total\ninternal energy of the ensemble (the Brown-York energy) vanishes, as does its\nvariation. Part of this vanishing variation is thermalized, captured by the\nhorizon entropy variation, and part is the matter contribution, which may or\nmay not be thermalized. If the matter is in global equilibrium at the de Sitter\ntemperature, the first law becomes the statement that the generalized entropy\nis stationary.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 24 Aug 2022 18:00:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 5 Sep 2022 19:59:40 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 12 Jan 2023 17:13:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-16"}
